<heading id="D0CE81A1FFD08039DFA3FD2AF116D3F4" centered="true" fontSize="10" level="2" pageId="3" pageNumber="456" reason="2">
<emphasis id="B94DEADFFFD08039DFA3FD2AF116D3F4" bold="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="456">
<taxonomicName id="4C394D4EFFD08039DFA3FD2AF117D3DB" authority="(Koch, 1803)" baseAuthorityName="Koch" baseAuthorityYear="1803" box="[719,1092,708,730]" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Mantura" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="456" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="chrysanthemi">
<emphasis id="B94DEADFFFD08039DFA3FD2AF6E0D3DB" bold="true" box="[719,947,708,730]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="456">Mantura chrysanthemi</emphasis>
(Koch, 1803)
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="4C394D4EFFD08039DF91FD0FF116D3F4" authority="Crotch, 1873" authorityName="Crotch" authorityYear="1873" box="[765,1093,735,757]" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Mantura" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="456" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="floridana">
<emphasis id="B94DEADFFFD08039DF91FD0FF6E4D3F4" bold="true" box="[765,951,735,757]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="456">Mantura floridana</emphasis>
Crotch, 1873
</taxonomicName>
</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8B8636CDFFD08039DFA9FCE5F100D419" blockId="3.[685,1173,778,1304]" pageId="3" pageNumber="456">
On 20 May in Northfield, 
<collectingRegion id="49FDF82FFFD08039DE9BFCE5F1C7D21E" box="[1015,1172,778,799]" country="United States of America" name="Massachusetts" pageId="3" pageNumber="456">Massachusetts</collectingRegion>
(
<geoCoordinate id="EE0D500AFFD08039DFD8FCCAF66CD23B" box="[692,831,805,826]" degrees="42.646967" direction="north" orientation="latitude" pageId="3" pageNumber="456" precision="1" value="42.64697">42.646967° N</geoCoordinate>
, 
<geoCoordinate id="EE0D500AFFD08039DE27FCCAF688D23B" box="[843,987,805,826]" degrees="72.424858" direction="west" orientation="longitude" pageId="3" pageNumber="456" precision="1" value="-72.42486">72.424858° W</geoCoordinate>
), I collected larvae of 
<taxonomicName id="4C394D4EFFD08039DFA2FCD0F6D1D254" box="[718,898,831,853]" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Mantura" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="456" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="chrysanthemi">
<emphasis id="B94DEADFFFD08039DFA2FCD0F6D1D254" box="[718,898,831,853]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="456">M. chrysanthemi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
mining leaves of 
<taxonomicName id="4C394D4EFFD08039D922FCD0F65ED271" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Polygonaceae" genus="Rumex" kingdom="Plantae" order="Caryophyllales" pageId="3" pageNumber="456" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="acetosella">
<emphasis id="B94DEADFFFD08039D922FCD0F65ED271" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="456">Rumex acetosella</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
L. (
<taxonomicName id="4C394D4EFFD08039DE5BFCB5F693D26E" box="[823,960,858,879]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Polygonaceae" kingdom="Plantae" order="Caryophyllales" pageId="3" pageNumber="456" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="family">Polygonaceae</taxonomicName>
). They fed for at least another four days before burrowing into soil and emerged as adults by 6 June. Comparing the mines with those from which I reared 
<taxonomicName id="4C394D4EFFD08039DE9FFC46F121D2BE" authorityName="Crotch" authorityYear="1873" box="[1011,1138,937,959]" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Mantura" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="456" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="floridana">
<emphasis id="B94DEADFFFD08039DE9FFC46F121D2BE" box="[1011,1138,937,959]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="456">M. floridana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
on 
<taxonomicName id="4C394D4EFFD08039DFC1FC2BF630D2DB" box="[685,867,964,986]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Polygonaceae" genus="Fallopia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Caryophyllales" pageId="3" pageNumber="456" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="scandens">
<emphasis id="B94DEADFFFD08039DFC1FC2BF630D2DB" box="[685,867,964,986]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="456">Fallopia scandens</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(L.) (
<taxonomicName id="4C394D4EFFD08039DECCFC2BF17AD2D8" box="[928,1065,964,985]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Polygonaceae" kingdom="Plantae" order="Caryophyllales" pageId="3" pageNumber="456" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="family">Polygonaceae</taxonomicName>
) (
<bibRefCitation id="EFA84B3CFFD08039D953FC2BF7B3D2F5" author="Eiseman" pageId="3" pageNumber="456" pagination="351 - 359" refId="ref3639" refString="Eiseman, C. S. 2014. New host records and other notes on North American leaf-mining Chrysomelidae (Coleoptera). The Coleopterists Bulletin 68 (3): 351 - 359." type="journal article" year="2014">Eiseman 2014</bibRefCitation>
), I do not believe they can be distinguished. However, a difference is apparent in my photographs of the larvae of the two species. Whereas in 
<taxonomicName id="4C394D4EFFD08039DFA5FBC1F63ED545" box="[713,877,1070,1092]" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Mantura" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="456" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="chrysanthemi">
<emphasis id="B94DEADFFFD08039DFA5FBC1F63ED545" box="[713,877,1070,1092]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="456">M. chrysanthemi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
the abdomen is covered with dark spots that show clearly through the leaf epidermis in my photographs of the mines, these spots are minute in 
<taxonomicName id="4C394D4EFFD08039DE5EFB91F6F9D595" authorityName="Crotch" authorityYear="1873" box="[818,938,1150,1172]" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Mantura" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="456" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="floridana">
<emphasis id="B94DEADFFFD08039DE5EFB91F6F9D595" box="[818,938,1150,1172]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="456">M. floridana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and the larva appears to be plain yellow when viewed through the leaf epidermis. The larger lateral spots on 
<taxonomicName id="4C394D4EFFD08039DE98FB5CF1C7D5C8" box="[1012,1172,1203,1225]" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Mantura" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="456" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="chrysanthemi">
<emphasis id="B94DEADFFFD08039DE98FB5CF1C7D5C8" box="[1012,1172,1203,1225]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="456">M. chrysanthemi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are about equal in width to the hind femur (
<figureCitation id="13022A48FFD08039D921FB21F1D4D5E2" box="[1101,1159,1230,1251]" captionStart="Figs" captionStartId="4.[197,238,1389,1408]" captionTargetBox="[173,1193,212,1343]" captionTargetId="figure-149@4.[173,1193,194,1366]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="Figs. 9–13. 9) Larva of Mantura chrysanthemi; 10) Larva of Mantura floridana; 11) Larva of Phyllotreta chalybeipennis; 12) Mostly linear mine of P. chalybeipennis; 13) Blotch mine of P. chalybeipennis, with one larva inside and one entering at right." pageId="3" pageNumber="456">Fig. 9</figureCitation>
), whereas on 
<taxonomicName id="4C394D4EFFD08039DE4BFB07F6F5D5FF" authorityName="Crotch" authorityYear="1873" box="[807,934,1256,1278]" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Mantura" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="456" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="floridana">
<emphasis id="B94DEADFFFD08039DE4BFB07F6F5D5FF" box="[807,934,1256,1278]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="456">M. floridana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
they are less than onethird the width of the hind femur (
<figureCitation id="13022A48FFD08039DE93FAECF114D419" box="[1023,1095,1283,1304]" captionStart="Figs" captionStartId="4.[197,238,1389,1408]" captionTargetBox="[173,1193,212,1343]" captionTargetId="figure-149@4.[173,1193,194,1366]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="Figs. 9–13. 9) Larva of Mantura chrysanthemi; 10) Larva of Mantura floridana; 11) Larva of Phyllotreta chalybeipennis; 12) Mostly linear mine of P. chalybeipennis; 13) Blotch mine of P. chalybeipennis, with one larva inside and one entering at right." pageId="3" pageNumber="456">Fig. 10</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
